ce:section.ce:para:
The PL emission properties of GQDs hold the key for their utilization in future optoelectronic-based applications [3]. In order to explore the PL properties of the synthesized GQDs, an excitation wavelength dependent PL measurement was carried out using different excitation wavelengths in the spectral range of 375–600nm. Fig. 6
                        a shows the excitation-wavelength-dependent PL emission spectra of synthesized GQDs dispersed in aqueous solution. It can be observed from the PL spectra, as shown in Fig. 6a that the emission peak shifts consistently from 398 (violet) to 505nm (green) when the excitation wavelength is changed from 375 to 450nm. In addition, it is also worthy to note that the intensity of the emission peak is increased as the excitation wavelength is increased. The present results indicate that the GQDs exhibit an excitation-dependent PL emission behavior similar to that reported earlier [9,64,65]. The PL emission peak shifts to the longer-wavelength side with an increase of the intensity for longer excitation wavelengths. The dependence of the emission wavelength and intensity of the emission peak on the excitation wavelength is a common phenomenon generally observed in carbon-based nanomaterials [66]. Some researchers have suggested that emissive traps, electronic conjugate structures, and free zigzag sites are the main reason for observing such phenomena [59,67,68]. On the other hand, Zhu et al. [69] have reported that the origin of such phenomena in GQDs strongly depends on the presence of surface states. The colorful PL emission behavior may be attributed to the chemical nature of GQDs edges also. The dissociation of NH3 leads to the formation of NH2 or NH species. The dissociated species of NH3 causes hydrogenation of OH and ring-opening of epoxy group (COC). The hydroxyl group shows higher reactivity toward abstracted hydrogen than the epoxy group. The epoxy group then reacts with NH2 or NH species and after the ring-opening of epoxy group, the newly formed −OH is eliminated by the second H atom abstraction from NH2. The de-epoxidation reaction can form OHN and OHN hydrogen bonds with NH2 or NH species. The surface reaction is mainly controlled by the ring opening of COC, the hydrogenation of the newly formed OH, and the successive hydrogen abstractions from NH3. The dissociation of NH3 and adsorption of its species on GO could be responsible for removal of the oxygen containing functional groups and modifying the electronic properties of GQDs [70]. As we know, the reduction of GO removes the oxygen containing functional groups attached with carbon atoms and also increases the formation of sp2-hybridized domains. The increased sp2-hybridized domains may have similarity in their size and surface states to those present in the GO before reduction. In addition, the removal of oxygen containing functional groups may also introduce defect states in the GQDs. Therefore, it is reasonable to believe that GQDs should exhibit excitation-dependent emission with increased intensity due to different emission sites of each sp2-cluster and defect states similar to those, which have been observed for most carbon-based nanomaterials [66]. Remarkably, it has been found that the shift between the energy of emission light and excitation light is almost the same. Fig. 6b shows the linear relationship between the energy of emission light and excitation light. The constant energy difference between emission and excitation light can be explained on the basis of a Stokes transition between π and σ orbitals (see Fig. 7
                        ). In the Stokes transition, the σ orbital electrons are excited to a high energy state (LUMO) and subsequently come back to the lower energy state of the π orbital. As a result, a constant energy difference between emission and excitation light is observed. For showing such a tendency, the energy difference should be less than 1.5eV [71]. It is worth to note that the energy difference between emission and excitation light in the present case is ∼0.3eV. The existence of such a low energy difference may be due to the presence of nitrogen (N) in NH3. The electronic arrangement of valence electrons in the nitrogen atom dominates by an additional energy state near the Fermi level. Consequently, the Fermi level shifts above the Dirac point, which induces an additional bandgap around the Dirac point in the system [72]. Thus, the energy difference is considerably lower in the present case. Hence, the present synthesis method could be useful for the development of GODs with different PL peaks (or colors). However, the exact mechanism responsible for the excitation-wavelength-dependent PL phenomenon in GQDs remains to be elucidated.
